documents.content: St. Croix expecting the worst from Hurricane Maria Some remaining residents of the heavily damaged Tutu Hi-Rise housing community had evacuated, Mapp said. Residents of the Seaview Nursing Home on St. Thomas had been relocated to Lockhart Elementary School in a separate wing from other shelter residents, officials said. Public officials have established shelters at the following places:  Lockhart Elementary in Estate Thomas, though V.I. Territorial Emergency Management Agency Director Mona Barnes said it was full.  Bertha C. Boschulte Middle School in Estate Bovoni, which was still accepting residents Tuesday morning.  Knud Hansen Health Complex, though Barnes said it, too had reached capacity.

metadata.title: St. Croix expecting the worst from Hurricane Maria

Paradise Jam hoops tourney relocating to mainland Tourney directors said they considered having St. Croix host the event after Hurricane Irma blew through St. Thomas on Sept. 6, but they were forced to look at other options when Hurricane Marias ferocious winds hit St. Croix on Wednesday, causing widespread damage to that island.

Having the tournament back on St. Thomas with accommodations aboard a docked cruise ship was one option Paradise Jam directors said they mulled over, but ultimately they decided that shifting the event to the mainland was the solution.

Each participating team in the 2017 mens and womens field has been sent a request for proposal, offering each university the opportunity to bid to host their respective events, the press release stated. Tournament directors said they will finalize locations by Friday.

More than a dozen teams were slated to participate in the tournament at the University of the Virgin Islands Sports and Fitness Center, starting on Nov. 17 and wrapping up on Nov. 25. This years mens lineup includes Wake Forest University, the alma mater of USVI and NBA basketball great Tim Duncan.

metadata.title: Paradise Jam hoops tourney relocating to mainland

documents.content: Federal disaster relief begins on St. Croix Officials also plan to begin food, water, and tarp distribution on St. Croix in the aftermath of the storm at four locations:  The Cotton Valley fire station.  Juanita Gardine Elementary School.  Alexander Henderson Junior High School.  St. Croix Educational Complex High School. Intitial distribution will begin today, in accordance with a curfew suspension between the hours of noon and 4 p.m., Mapp said. Officials said Thursday that distribution will be limited to one case of MREs and three liters of water, but additional supplies could arrive before noon today, which would allow more supplies to be distributed, he said. Distribution sites on St. Thomas also will resume giving out MREs. water and tarps today, according to Mapp.

metadata.title: Federal disaster relief begins on St. Croix
